>
  <p>AUSTIN, Texas — October 1, 2025 — As part of its ongoing mission to support and strengthen the open source community, OpenTeams, the global leader in open source AI, was proud to sponsor the development of Python: The Documentary, a feature-length film exploring the origins of Python, through interviews with its foundational contributors, revealing how a side project in the 1990s became the foundation of AI and modern computing. The documentary was also sponsored by PyCharm JetBrains IDE, Anaconda, Dropbox, Meta and Quansight.</p>

  <p>The documentary was produced by <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/cult-repo/?originalSubdomain=ie" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CultRepo</a>, a fully independent production company committed to telling the human stories behind technology. The documentary features interviews with Python’s core contributors, including creator Guido van Rossum, longtime developer Raymond Hettinger, and <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/teoliphant/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Travis Oliphant</a>, Chief AI Architect and Founder of OpenTeams and NumPy creator.</p>

  <p>The full documentary is <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GfH4QL4VqJ0" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">now available</a> to watch for free on YouTube.</p>

  <p>To showcase the film and bring together the open source community, OpenTeams hosted two invitation-only premiere screenings in Austin, TX, and London, UK. Each event brought together members of the open-source community, engineers, clients and partners. The screenings also included Q&amp;As with Oliphant, offering a unique opportunity to hear firsthand reflections on the history and future of computing.</p>

  <p>“Python was born from the open source technology community; software engineers who worked together, shared ideas and built upon each other’s success to create a new, easier way to code,” said Oliphant. “As AI development and adoption continue to accelerate, it is critical to remember the human stories that make it all possible. I am honored to be one piece of the open source legacy, and to continue to support the community’s efforts through the work we are doing at OpenTeams.”</p>

  <p>In addition to the 90-minute documentary, CultRepo featured Oliphant in a “mini-doc” on <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-xhai2iu_QY&amp;t=74s" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">The early days of scientific Python</a>. The supplemental video tells the story of Oliphant’s early career and his development of NumPy, an open-source library for numerical and scientific computing, which has enabled the widespread adoption of Python.</p>

